  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions that address money laundering. Here's a breakdown:\n\n**Key International Conventions and Bodies:**\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (Vienna Convention) - 1988:** This is one of the earliest international agreements addressing money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention) - 2000:** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug-related crimes to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, including corruption, trafficking in persons, and other forms of organized crime.  It also emphasizes international cooperation.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (Merida Convention) - 2003:** This convention focuses on corruption-related money laundering, requiring countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from corruption offenses.\n\n*   **",
